issue.title: Segfault at onnx export of fp16 model.

labels.name: triaged
labels.description: This issue has been looked at a team member, and triaged and prioritized into an appropriate module

repository.name: pytorch
repository.description: Tensors and Dynamic neural networks in Python with strong GPU acceleration

issue.body:
## 🐛 Bug
When I export an fp16 model from Pytorch (1.7.1) to onnx with jit decorator I get segfault. Please, see the output below.

```
1.7.1
{'o': tensor([[0.3491, 0.9634, 0.3867, 0.0742, 0.5737, 0.4253, 0.9653, 0.7935, 0.5679,
         0.4507],
        [0.4006, 0.1095, 0.9175, 0.6177, 0.2668, 0.5767, 0.0000, 0.0000, 0.0000,
         0.0000]], device='cuda:0', dtype=torch.float16)}
Warning: ONNX Scalar Type Analysis - Scalar types mismatch for tensor inputs of operator onnx::Mul. Please report a bug to PyTorch. The scalar type Half of the first tensor is chosen.
Segmentation fault (core dumped)
```

## To Reproduce

Run script below

```python
import onnxruntime
from torch import nn
import torch

print(torch.__version__)

@torch.jit.script
def compute_output_lengths(x, lengths_fraction):
	if lengths_fraction is None:
		return torch.full(x.shape[:1], x.shape[-1], device = x.device, dtype = torch.long)
	return (lengths_fraction * x.shape[-1]).ceil().long()

@torch.jit.script
def temporal_mask(x, lengths):
	return (torch.arange(x.shape[-1], device = x.device, dtype = torch.long).unsqueeze(0) <
			lengths.unsqueeze(1)).view(x.shape[:1] + (1, ) * (len(x.shape) - 2) + x.shape[-1:])

class Model(nn.Module):
	def forward(self, x, xlen):
		l = compute_output_lengths(x, xlen)
		tm = temporal_mask(x, l)
		x = x * tm
		return dict(o=x)

model = Model()
model.to(dtype=torch.float16, device='cuda')

x = torch.rand(2, 10).to(dtype=torch.float16, device='cuda')
xlen = torch.rand(2).to(dtype=torch.float16, device='cuda')

print(model(x, xlen))

torch.onnx.export(
		model, (x, xlen),
		'fp16_jit_repro.onnx',
		verbose=False,
		opset_version=12,
		export_params=None,
		do_constant_folding=True,
		input_names=['x', 'xlen']
)

print('runtime...')
runtime = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('fp16_jit_repro.onnx')
print(runtime.run(None, dict(x=x.cpu().numpy(), xlen=xlen.cpy().numpy())))
```

class Model(nn.Module):
	def forward(self, x, xlen):

model.to(device='cuda')

x = torch.rand(2, 10).to( device='cuda')
xlen = torch.rand(2).to( device='cuda')

print(model(x, xlen))

torch.onnx.export(

		export_params=None,
		do_constant_folding=True,
		input_names=['x', 'xlen']
)

runtime = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('fp32_jit_prim_dtype_repro.onnx')
print(runtime.run(None, dict(x=x.cpu().numpy(), xlen=xlen.cpu().numpy())))

## Environment

 - ONNX Runtime version: onnxruntime-1.6.0
 - Python version: Python 3.8
 - Pytorch version: 1.7.1
 - How you installed PyTorch (`conda`, `pip`, source): conda
 - CUDA/cuDNN version: CUDA Version: 10.2
 - GPU model and memory: Tesla V100 (32G)

But then I got another fail and opened an issue at onnxruntime repo. See here https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/7098

body:
Seems like an exporter problem where ```(1, ) * (len(x.shape) - 2)``` was handled incorrectly as Mul op. In PyTorch, the output is an empty tuple since len(x.shape) -2 = 0, while in the exported model it becomes a scalar 0. @spandantiwari

Below are the logs from symbolic shape inference:
```
Gather: Gather_32
  Input 0: 33 
  Input 1: 32 
  34: [1] 7
  Sympy Data: [2]
Squeeze: Squeeze_33
  Input 0: 34 
  35: [] 7
  Sympy Data: [2]
Constant: Constant_34
  36: [] 7
  Sympy Data: 2
Sub: Sub_35
  Input 0: 35 
  Input 1: 36 
  37: [] 7
  Sympy Data: [0]
Constant: Constant_36
  38: [1] 7
  Sympy Data: [1]
Mul: Mul_37
  Input 0: 38 
  Input 1: 37 
  39: [1] 7
  Sympy Data: [0] *** this is incorrect ***
Concat: Concat_38
  Input 0: 30 
  Input 1: 39 
  40: [2] 7
  Sympy Data: [2, 0]
```

issue.title: [ONNX] Incorrect handling of tuple multiplication with zero

labels.name: triaged
labels.description: This issue has been looked at a team member, and triaged and prioritized into an appropriate module

repository.name: pytorch
repository.description: Tensors and Dynamic neural networks in Python with strong GPU acceleration

issue.body:
## 🐛 Bug

Opening this issue based on ONNXRuntime issue https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/7098 as issue is relevant to exporter and not ONNXRuntime

Currently, cases in which two tuples are mutliplied is handled incorrectly in ONNX export
For example in ```x.shape[:1] + (1, ) * (len(x.shape) - 2) + x.shape[-1:])``` and ```len(x.shape) = 2``` we get a scenario where
 ```(1,)*0=()```, but exporter treats it as [0], causing shape mismatch in the Mul operator

## To Reproduce

Model code to reproduce error
```
import onnxruntime
from torch import nn
import torch

print(torch.__version__)

@torch.jit.script
def compute_output_lengths(x, lengths_fraction):
    return (lengths_fraction * x.shape[-1]).ceil().long()

@torch.jit.script
def temporal_mask(x, lengths):
    tup_prod = (1,) * (len(x.shape) - 2)
    return (torch.arange(x.shape[-1], dtype=lengths.dtype).unsqueeze(0) <
            lengths.unsqueeze(1)).view(x.shape[:1] + tup_prod + x.shape[-1:])

class Model(nn.Module):
    def forward(self, x, xlen):
        l = compute_output_lengths(x, xlen)
        tm = temporal_mask(x, l)
        return x * tm

model = Model()

x = torch.rand(2, 10)
xlen = torch.rand(2)

print(model(x, xlen))

torch.onnx.export(
        model, (x, xlen),
        'fp32_jit_prim_dtype_repro.onnx',
        verbose=True,
        opset_version=14,
        input_names=['x', 'xlen']
)

runtime = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('fp32_jit_prim_dtype_repro.onnx')
print(runtime.run(None, dict(x=x.cpu().numpy(), xlen=xlen.cpu().numpy())))
```

## Expected behavior

Inference without ONNXRuntimeError

body: Opened similar issue in PyTorch, maybe we can close the issue here

This seems like a export issue. We have opened an item under PyTorch for this: https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/issues/55597, and will investigate this.

@II245 Please stay tuned to that thread. We will close this one here.
